<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-939-256  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 939 256.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Language  Nov 1989 v6 n11 p113(12)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Miller Freeman Publications 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multitasking operating system enhancements for the 386. (SoftwareReview) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Parker, Tim.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Eight multitasking software packages for the 80386 are reviewed.andO;Each one can create, control and manipulate the 80386's protectedmodes and allow one or multiple users to process several taskssimultaneously.andP;  Each was tested under single-task, multiple-taskand, when applicable, multi-user, multitask conditions.andP;  Theproducts reviewed are: Digital Research Inc's Concurrent DOS 3863.0, Quarterdeck Office Systems' Desqview 386 2.25, Alloy ComputerProducts' 386/Multiware, StarPath Systems Inc's Vmos/3 G3, SunnyHill Software's Omniview 4.13, The Software Link's PC-MOS 3.0,Intelligent Graphics Corp's VM/386 1.22, and Microsoft Corp'sWindows/386 2.11.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Research Inc. (products)Quarterdeck Office Systems (products)Alloy Computer Products Inc. (products)StarPath Systems Inc. (products)Sunny Hill Software (products)Software Link Inc. (products)Intelligent Graphics Corp. (products)Microsoft Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    ALOY; MSFT.andO;Product:   Intel 80386 (Microprocessor) (computer programs)Concurrent DOS 386 3.0 (Operating system)DESQview 386 2.25 (Utility program)386-MultiWare (Operating system)Vmos/3 G3 (Operating system)Omniview 4.13 (Operating system)PC-MOS 3.0 (Operating system)VM/386 1.22 (Operating system)Windows/386 2.11 (Computer program).andO;Topic:     MultitaskingEvaluationOperating SystemsEnhancementsOperating Environments.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Multitasking operating system enhancements for the 386 The power of the Intel80386 CPU is much greater than most users require for a single task.andP;  The80386, with its built in 8086 emulation mode, is ideal for software thatexpands the capability of the older chip.andP;  By operating the 80386 in 8086mode, several virtual machines can operate simultaneously.andM;The 8086 virtual machines allow the 80386 to process several tasksconcurrently.andP;  The tasks can all be controlled by one user, providingmultitasking, or each task can be a different user connected through someterminal device.andP;  In multiuser systems, each user can themselves accessmultiple 8086 virtual machines.andM;The multitasking software reviewed here creates, controls, and manipulatesthe 80386's protected modes.andP;  Each system permits one or more users toconcurrently process several tasks.andM;Some of the reviewed software allows only one user to multitask, while othersallow multiple users, each perhaps using multiple tasks.andM;The testing team for this review included five professional programmers andanalysts.andP;  Each piece of software was used by at least two people for aminimum of one week.andM;Each piece of software was tested under single-task, multipletask, and whereapplicable, multiuser, multitask conditions.andP;  Application loads varied fromlight to very heavy.andP;  Both single-user and multiuser versions of standardapplications were used, as were some esoteric software andterminate-and-stay-resident (TSR) programs.andM;Test equipment varied with each reviewer, but the reference system was a Dell325 with 80387, 150MB hard disk, 8MB RAM, and VGA display.andP;  We used DOS 3.3.andO;</TEXT></DOC>